1. Label & Selector:
We can select the kubernetes object with type, function and etc....

label the object first - objects like pod, replicaset, deployment, service......

use selector to the select the object with the labels.

If replicaset is created with a label app=app1 then the pod should have the same label app=app1. Selector will match the labels now.


2. Taints & Tolerations:
Taint will be set on Node. 
Tolerations will be set on Pods.

Taint set on Node will accept the only pods which toleration for the particular node. But tolerate pods can place it on any other nodes too.

Note: Basically pods will be placed on Worker node not on master node. So, taint will be set on Master node to accept the tolerate pods.

Apply taint on node, apply tolerate on pod then tolerate pod will be assigned to taint node.

NoSchedule: Don't enter into room. (pod won't assign to the nodes unless it has tolerations)
PreferNoSchedule: Avoid entering the room. (if pod is not assigned anywhere then it can assign to node has PreferNoSchedule)
NoExecute: Don't enter + remove from the room (pod won't assign to the nodes and also assigned pods will be removed quickly)


3. Node Selectors:
Pod can be assinged to the Nodes based on the node selection, First label the nodes with key/value
Assign a node selector in the pod and select the nodes.

a. kubectl label node node01 size=large

b. Pod.yml
apiVersion:
kind:
metadata:
  name: myapp
  type:
spec:
 container:
  Image:
 nodeselector:
  size: Large

Now myapp pod only select the node01


4. Node affinity
Pods can be assigned to the Nodes with the set of rules with the node affinity. 
In the node affinity rule:
operator says In, NotIn, Exist
Key: size
Value:
-Large
-Medium

Types of node affinity: Available
requiredDuringSchedulingignoredDuringExecution
PreferredDuringSchedulingignoredDuringExecution

# High performance pod to assign on node
requiredDuringSchedulingignoredDuringExecution: Scenario 1 & 2
Scenario 1: if labels are assigned to the node, Pods will be setup with the matching labels on the Node. If no labels on the node then pods won't
assigng. (required during scdehuling)
Scenario 2:If pods are already exist and if labels are removed from the node, then pods will continue (ignored during execution)

# low performance pod to assign on node
PreferredDuringSchedulingignoredDuringExecution: Scenario 3 & 4
Scenario 3: if labels are assigned not assigned to the node, Pods will be setup on the Node based on Node availability and ignore affinity rules. 
(preferred during scheduling)
Scenario 4:If pods are already exist and if labels are removed from the node, then pods will continue (ignored during execution)


5. Taints & Tolerations vs Node affinity:
Taints & Tolerations:
3 Nodes & 3 Pods (taint nodes with colors blue, green, red) (tolerate pods with color blue, green, red)
Matching the toleration pods with the taint nodes. 
Note: Pod can assign to any other pods without taint apply.

Node Affinity:
Label the node with color.
Set affinity rules with the pod.
Affinity rules in the pod should match with the lables in the node. Also there is no mandatory to place to affinity rules pod to label nodes. It can
be set anywhere.

Note:
If we use both: T&T and Node Affinity
The respective color pods will be apply on the color nodes. Other pods can be assigned on the other nodes. 

6. Resoruce Requirements:
Node will have CPU and Memory to place the pods.
Pods will be placed on the respective nodes where the resources are highly available.

Resource request:
Assign a reqeust of cpu and memory to the Pod.

Resoruce Limits:
Limiting the resoruce for the pod.

Exceed limits:
After limiting the resoruces to the pods, when its exceeds the CPU it will be throttle and pods cannot use more cpu than the limit.
But in the case of memory, pods can use more memory than the limits. If it's exceeds the limit then CPU and Memory resoruce gets decreased &
pods will be in terminate state (out of memory - oom)

Behaviour CPU
Request & Limit:
A. No request & No limits - Pod A & B can consume the CPU but Pod A might consume all the CPU. Other pods might face lack of CPU resources. 
B. No request & limits - Pod A & B can consume more CPU but the limit exceeds.
C. Request & Limits - Pod A & B might have 1 CPU but limit exceeds.
D. Request & No limits - Pod A & B might have 1 CPU but there is no limits. 

Behaviour Memory
Request & Limit:
A. No request & No limits - Pod A & B can consume the memory but Pod A might consume all the memory. Other pods might face lack of memory resources. 
B. No request & limits - Pod A & B can consume more memory but the limit exceeds. Out of Memory - pod terminate
C. Request & Limits - Pod A & B might have 1M memory but limit exceeds. Out of Memory - pod terminate 
D. Request & No limits - Pod A & B might have 1M memory but there is no limits. Avoiding OOM


Limit Range: It is used to define the defauly CPU resoruces for the container. Resource request, Resource limit, minimum and maximum CPU set.
Same limit range set will be applicable to the memory.

Resource Quotas:
We can set the reqeust and limit as maximum and minimum for the CPU and Memory to all the pods in the node.
Just setup the things in the namespace level.



7. DaemonSets:
DaemonSets use to assing a pod to all nodes in the cluster while creating the DaemonSets.
Also, in use cases it use to set monitoring or logging agents on all nodes.

Note: Without DeamonSets, if we want to assign each pods to each nodes, we need to configure the node details in each pods.


8. Static Pods:
Only kubelet will take care of the all the things in static pods. It will monitor the pods, it will delete the pods based on yml config and
auto-heal the pods if it is deleted.

There are no Control plane and No kube proxy and No worker node 

Only Kubelet and container run time (pods will be created)
pod.yml file will be placed in the specifc path to create the pods.
example: /etc/kubernetes/manifest

Instead of searching for the static path we can config the yml file details in the configuration and configure the static path details
in the yml.

In use cases:
Control plane components are handled as static pod, so pods will be healthy and deleted based on yaml configuration.
In the yaml we can handle the kube-api-server complete info, instead of running it manually to bring it up.


Static pods vs Daemonsets
1. Created by kubelet vs created by kube-api-server 
2. Deploy control plane components vs deploy logging or monioring agents on all nodes.

Both ignored by the kube-scheduler


9. Priority classes
If there are 100 pods in the cluster. 

We have 3 nodes and 100 pods. We can define the high priority for some pods and low for others.
Only high priority pods will be deployed first and with the remaining resources low priority will take place.

First create yaml definition for priority class set. Value and Preempting

Apply the priority to the pods, by default the prioirty value will be zero in the pods.

1 billion value is high prioirty and -2billion is low priority.
2 billion value is used for high peroformance like control plane components.

preemptionPolicy: Never (never delete other pods to allocate it themselves)
preemptionPolicy: high (will delete low prioriy pods, high pods will be in priority even low is exist)
preemptionPolicy: low (if pod is assigned with nothing and other is lower preemptionpolicy then imporatant is given to policy added one)


10. Multiple Schedulers:
Apart from default kube schedulers, we can create a multiple schedulers to assign a pod to the nodes in the custom way.

pod or deployment yaml file will have the configuration to map the new scheduler yaml file location path details.

my-new-scheduler.yaml will consists of new scheduler details.

11. Configuring Schedule profiles:
Instead of creating a multiple scheduler in a separate profile, we can create all the schedulers in a sinle profile.
Each profile can define a scheduler plugin and extension.

Scheduler plugin:
Scheduler queue(priority sort): It will check the priority classes and with high prioiry pods will go first.

Filtering(noderesourcefit, nodename, nodeunschedule, taintandtolerations, node affinity): 
Filter the nodes with the resources: pod need 10GI, 2 CPU then it will check the high available nodes and filter it.

Scoring(noderesourcefit, nodename, imagelocality, taintandtolerations, node affinity):
Scoring is based on the nodes resources, if we have 2 nodes with 4CPU 20GI and 6CPU 40GI then second node score is high for the pods.

Binding(default binder): Based on the queue, filter, score the binding will happen.



Extension points:
Scheduler queue: queue
Filter: Pre filter, filter, post filter
Score: pre score, score, reserve
Binding: Permit, prebind, bind, postbind


12. Admission Controllers:

# kubectl create -f pod.yml

Kube control inform Kube-Apiserver about the creation of Pods, Kube-Apiserver will do Authentication and Authorization and sends the 
info to kubelet to perform the actions.

Authentication - Whether the user is valid or not to perform the actions.
Authorization - RBAC - whether the user has the Role to control the actions like get, list, create, update.

But the user doesn't have the actions to control the pod creation like the image should not pull from Public Registry like docker hub,
not run as a roor user, without namespce the pod creation should not happen.........

So, here Adimission Controller plays a major role after authentication & authorization. They control the plugins like namespacelifecycle,
Priority, Deafultstorageclass, Defaultingressclass, resroucequota by enabling in the pod creation of Kube-Apiserver.yml files from the 
path etc/kubernetes/manifests/

or 

enable with kube.apiserver.service


13. Validating and Mutating admission controllers:

Validating admission controllers: "Namespaceexist" if the pod has to create then at first it will check the namespace exist or not. Based on
the availability the request will allowed or denied.

Mutating admission controllers: "defaultstorageclass" If the volume has to create then at first it will check the storage class is defined
or not. If not then the default will set it to storage class in the volume.

Validating and Mutating both works in different scenario:
Scenario 1:
Mutating "Namesapceautoprovision" if the namespace not exist "provison takes place"
Validating "namespaceexist" Based on the available namespace with mutating "reqeust takes place"

Scenario 2:
Validating "namespaceexist" the reqeuest will be denied if namespace not exist.
Steps on Mutating "Namesapceautoprovision" will not happend because valdiating admission controllers rejects the request. 


We can custom our own mutating and valdiating admission controllers using webhook server and configuration.

Webhook configuration will be written in yaml file:
It has webhook server details to send the request and receive the response.

Webhook server:
It will be written in any programming language and it has the valdiating and mutating details. What Reqeust to recieve and
response to be sent in json format.







